# Fluff Date: 2026-02-10 14:00:04
overview:<p>The Amarok is a 100-ton Clan assault BattleMech introduced in 3149, designed specifically to counteract the Death From Above tactics increasingly employed by Clan Jade Falcon. Conceived by a Clan Wolf scientist who turned to Clan Sea Fox for manufacturing assistance, the Amarok borrows heavily from the Sea Fox Hammerhead design, particularly its use of hardened armor and modified hand actuators for close combat. Built at Manufacturing Plant SFF-TU1 on Tukayyid, the design represents an unusual collaborative effort between Clan Wolf and Clan Sea Fox, made possible by a special arrangement granting extensive access to the ilKhanate's industrial resources following the upheaval of Gray Monday. Despite political friction (including unsuccessful Trials waged by the Sea Foxes over perceived design element theft) demand among Clan Wolf warriors remains exceptionally high, with MechWarriors competing in Trials of Possession for assignment to the chassis.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Amarok mounts twenty and a half tons of hardened armor, providing exceptional physical protection that reflects its intended role as a close-combat anti-DFA platform. A Type 79 400-rated XL fusion engine provides a base speed of 54 kph, supplemented by a supercharger that pushes the assault 'Mech to 75 kph in short bursts, speed unusual for its weight class. The primary armament is entirely torso-mounted: an extended-range PPC fitted with a capacitor delivers a devastating long-range punch capable of disrupting the flight path of incoming 'Mechs, while a rotary autocannon/5 and large pulse laser sustain damage at medium ranges. Paired Streak SRM-6 launchers handle close engagements with reliable accuracy.</p><p>The Amarok's most distinctive feature is a pre-programmed defensive routine designed to lock the arms together above the cockpit, shielding the pilot from DFA impacts. Based on Solaris VII combat data and the Hammerhead's physical layout, this system suffered from severe reliability issues ranging from simple activation failures to catastrophic arm collisions with the 'Mech's own upper torso and cockpit. Most MechWarriors permanently disable the feature, and it is scheduled for removal from future production runs. The Amarok's Battlefist-equipped arms and inherent stability compensate effectively, providing devastating melee capability even without the automated defense system.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced in 3150, the Amarok 2 trades the base model's raw firepower for significantly enhanced mobility, adding MASC to reach speeds comparable to the Executioner. The rotary autocannon is removed entirely, and the Streak SRM launchers give way to a Streak LRM-20 with two tons of ammunition for long-range engagement capability. An Improved Heavy Large Laser provides devastating close-range firepower, while twin AP Gauss Rifles and a trio of ER Medium Lasers distributed across the arms and head ensure the variant remains dangerous at any distance. CASE II protects the ammunition bays, producing a viable ranged combatant that retains the chassis's inherent capability against physical attacks.</p>

history:<p>The Amarok emerged from the political dynamics of the post-Gray Monday ilClan era. With the ilKhanate's standing diminished among the other Khanates, a special order from Clan Wolf initiated a collaboration with Clan Sea Fox to reverse the Wolves' declining military fortunes. The arrangement granted Clan Wolf extensive access to Sea Fox industrial resources on Tukayyid, though it provoked dissent between the Khanates when it became clear how heavily the new design drew upon the Hammerhead. Trials of Possession and Refusal waged by the Wolves over various design elements and the initial production run were defeated, allowing Manufacturing Plant SFF-TU1 to supply significant numbers of the new assault 'Mech in record time.</p><p>Clan Wolf's leadership intended to distribute Amaroks across multiple Clusters as specialist anti-DFA platforms, particularly to counter major Jade Falcon threats. In practice, production limitations restricted deployment to a handful of Clusters, primarily within Alpha and Beta Galaxies. The design saw its first major combat test during the battle for Skye, where both its strengths and its flaws were prominently displayed.</p><p>The Nineteenth Wolf Striker Cluster's Amaroks performed effectively during fighting around the Sanglamore Academy campus, operating in groups to pull down Shrikes, Turkinas, and Jade Hawks attempting Death From Above attacks. When confronted by the concentrated firepower of the Turkina Keshik, however, the Amaroks were overwhelmed by sheer volume of fire. The Ninth Wolf Guard fared considerably better, using their Amaroks to ambush the Turkina Keshik. Leveraging the 'Mech's supercharged speed to engage without hindrance, they routed the Keshik and eliminated stragglers one by one.</p><p>The Sea Foxes ultimately waged a series of Trials over design element theft from the Hammerhead, though all proved unsuccessful. Despite the political friction surrounding its creation, the Amarok remains one of the most sought-after assault 'Mechs in the Clan Wolf touman, with warriors eagerly competing for the privilege of piloting one.</p>

